<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-721-621  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 721 621.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Dec 17 1990 v7 n49 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>VP shuffle highlights DEC service reorganization. (EnterpriseIntegration Services and Customer Services form one group led byRussell Gullotti)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jenkins, Avery.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (Officials and employees).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     ReorganizationSupport ServicesExecutivePromotion of EmployeeComputer Systems Integration.andO;Person:    Gullotti, Russell (Selection and appointment); Zereski, Donald(Selection and appointment); Grainger, David (Selection andappointment).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>VP shuffle highlights DEC service reorganizationandM;In a move that transforms DEC's service operation, the company last weekreorganized two key operations and posted three executives to new positions.andM;DEC combined its Enterprise Integration Services and its Customer Servicesinto one group headed by Russell Gullotti, vice president of corporateservices.andM;At the same time, Donald Zereski, formerly DEC's vice president of CustomerServices, was promoted to vice president of the U.S.andP;  area, expanding hisresponsibility to include product delivery as well as the sales and servicesfunctions formerly overseen by David Grainger.andM;Grainger, who was the vice president of U.S.andP;  sales and services, has beenappointed to the new created post of vice president of the OEM/Value-AddedReseller Business Group, a worldwide group responsible for managing DEC'sindirect sales channels.andM;The three executives will continue to report to Jack Smith, DEC's senior vicepresident of operations.andM;The key shift was Grainger's move out of sales and services, said Nili Young,vice president of midrange strategies for the Meta Group, a consultingcompany in Westport, Conn.andM;DEC's fiscal situation is not looking up, Young said, and Grainger'sdeparture and the subsequent shakeup was the result of Smith's attempt toinstall a more customer-receptive management group.andM;&quot;[Grainger] was of the old Digital mentality,&quot; she said.andM;Zereski, Grainger's replacement, comes from the customer service side of theorganization, and will likely be better received by DEC's large customers,she said.andM;DEC's shipments have been off 20 percent each quarter, and acceptance wasdelayed for 26 of the 122 VAX 9000s slated to be shipped during this quarter,Young said.andM;Separately, Mark Steinkrauss, DEC's director of investor relations, said DEChas &quot;sufficient funds in reserve&quot; to accommodate the 5,000 to 6,000additional employees it is attempting to trim from its roster this year.andM;Also last week, Data General's board of directors asked company chairman andfounder Edson de Castro to step down.andO;</TEXT></DOC>